Last year I with my  daughter and son went to see Bob and Neil in Ireland, all the mod cons now but still closed my eyes and dreamt  Great to be on the same soil as these two Geniuses. 50 years down the road and lnothing visual to work with on this song, so I close my eyes,listen and realize that the Genius has presented us with another Masterpiece. Thank you Mr Zimmerman.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was in the third grade when President Kennedy was assassinated. I recall a teacher coming into the room and spoke with our teacher. they both walked out into the hallway and soon others came out and I saw many of them were crying. We weren't told anything about what was going on. I don't recall if the school was let out or we stayed. Later on though, when I did get home, I saw the news and then the footage of Kennedy being murdered in black and white. It was my first footage of an actual murder being played out on television. It was the first moment that this nation would be forced to face a new reality of what was about to come. It was a shedding of innocence that would not be recovered. We would not be the same nation again. Lee Harvey Oswald would be the second murder to play out in black and white across the nation. The nation was being forced to grow up to this new world as new challenges kept coming. The Vietnam War, the killing fields of Khmer Rouge, napalm carpet bombing, the murders of Robert Kennedy and Martin Luther King, Jr., all played out in black and white.


Time it was and what
a Time it was, it was
A time of innocence
A time of confidences

Long ago it must be
I have a photograph
Preserve your memories
They're all that's left you

snippet.textDisplay:
There is a line in the song "Series of Dreams" that I believe is a reference to the JFK assassination. That line is “…Dreams where the umbrella is folded*…”. This is, I believe, an oblique reference to the infamous “Umbrella Man” and the theory that his umbrella was a signalling device for the assassins (that’s plural). The song is about a “series of dreams” and contains references to random images and incongruous scenarios which reflect the kaleidoscopic, narrative sequences of the dream state. If the image(s) are interpreted as having any meaning at all, then I believe one would naturally interpret an image of a “folded” umbrella as significant only as it applies to the scenario in Dallas where the umbrella was *unfolded or open. Dylan is putting this image into a meaningful context by using the pronoun “where” as opposed to “when”. Dreams “when” an umbrella is folded could refer to a multitude of scenarios from rain showers to hot, sunny days, where one might open and close (unfold or fold) an umbrella for a variety of reasons. But “dreams where the umbrella is folded” seems to put the scenario in the context of a specific place and time, namely, Dealey Plaza, November 22nd, 1963.
It would seem that he is obviously making reference to the only umbrella in our history that has any meaningful significance in the fact of it being either opened or closed. In fact, this umbrella has meaning in the fact that it was indeed open (unfolded) on that day in Dallas, whether as a pointed protest "aimed" at JFK, or to serve a more sinister purpose in signalling those truly aiming at Kennedy to fire and effect a change that our country and the world is still challenged by to this very day. “Dreams where the umbrella is folded” seems to me to indicate the dreamer is wondering “what if…” the umbrella had not been “unfolded”, and the signal had not been given to the shooters, and JFK had gone on to reelection, and the course of history had not been changed by unseen hands on the levers of fate. The fault is not in our stars, but in ourselves. Ad hominem. Casus belli.
